english:
  title: Written on a Poetry Scroll of Anurak Island by Jeoja
  author: Kang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Look there—Jeoja Island leans across the midstream,
    its twin stone heads half-emerging from the wave-heart.
    After centuries of wind and dust accumulate,
    it transforms to stone and becomes a wooded hill.

    Silver waves encircle on all sides, gleaming in the void—
    its form seems to dance and play in empty air.
    Blue rattan and green pine stand thick and intertwined,
    while within them golden walls open in a tower.

    Once I heard the sound of jade pendants ring and shimmer,
    spring and autumn turned among silk robes and brocade.
    But those days of revelry have faded with the seasons,
    and flute songs ceased as twilight settled on the river.

    Now a clear and handsome heir, a true king's son,
    inherits these lands and frames his fresh designs.
    He clears the tangled thorns and restores what had decayed—
    joy rises like mist above the waters.

    Day after day he sits in idleness, forgetting care,
    seeking where beauty hides in stillness and mystery.
    Spring rains darken the fragrant grasses of the field,
    while evening mist brings white gulls to the sandy shore.

    River clouds lie thick and starlight fades to black,
    the turbid waves churn restless—even fish-dragons grieve.
    Water falls, the river empties, wild geese fly low,
    and reeds on both banks tremble cold in wind.

    At dusk the snow descends, darkness swallows earth,
    and one angler sits alone in his small boat.
    Four seasons adorn this solitary isle—
    the master's unrestrained spirit never rests.

    Drunk, he takes his brush to paint this strange beauty,
    capturing each delicate hue without omission.
    But my aged verse-craft has grown weak and tired,
    and I can only hum a hundredth part of its worth.

    When shall we be drunk together, sleeping under our boat,
    exchanging songs—ai-ya, ai-ya—with the river's flow?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jeoja Island: An island in the Han River near Seoul, known for its natural beauty and cultural significance.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Twin stone heads emerging from water: A poetic reference to the distinctive rock formations visible at the island.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jade pendants and silk robes: References to the refined pleasures and entertainments of the past, suggesting the island''s history as a place of elegance.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'King''s son: The heir who has taken responsibility for maintaining and beautifying the island.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'ai-ya, ai-ya: The traditional Korean boatman''s song (欸乃), transcribed here to preserve the poetic effect of river workers'' calls.'
  - key: ''
    value: The poem concludes with an invitation to share wine and song on the river, a classical Chinese poetic gesture of friendship and harmony with nature.
